   "start": 10.46,
   "end": 12.74,
   "text": "sun sometimes doesn't come up until 10 in the morning."
  },
  {
   "start": 13.38,
   "end": 17.64,
   "text": "Geographically, China is about as wide as the United States, which uses 4 separate"
  },
  {
   "start": 17.64,
   "end": 22.64,
   "text": "time zones, so China should have roughly 5, but in 1949, the new government scrapped"
  },
  {
   "start": 22.64,
   "end": 27.34,
   "text": "them all and put the whole nation on one time, Beijing time, as a symbol of national"
  },
  {
   "start": 27.34,
   "end": 27.74,
   "text": "unity."
  },
  {
   "start": 27.74,
   "end": 31.28,
   "text": "One country, one clock, near Beijing, that's fine."
  },
  {
   "start": 31.88,
   "end": 36.78,
   "text": "But thousands of kilometers west, in Xinjiang, the official time is wildly out of step with"
  },
  {
   "start": 36.78,
   "end": 37.18,
   "text": "the sky."
  },
  {
   "start": 37.64,
   "end": 42.26,
   "text": "In winter, sunrise can come around 10am, and the sun can still be up late into the evening,"
  },
  {
   "start": 42.4,
   "end": 46.16,
   "text": "so people out there quietly run their lives on an unofficial Xinjiang time."
  },
  {
   "start": 46.8,
   "end": 52.04,
   "text": "Two hours behind Beijing, the buses, the shops, when you meet for dinner, ask someone"
  },
  {
   "start": 52.04,
   "end": 55.84,
   "text": "the time, and you might have to ask back, Beijing time or our time."
  },
  {
   "start": 55.84,
   "end": 60.28,
   "text": "A single time zone keeps the country on the same page, but the sun doesn't take orders"
  },
  {
   "start": 60.28,
   "end": 64.72,
   "text": "from Beijing, so half a content in a way, people just quietly made their own time anyway."
  },
  {
   "start": 65.26,
   "end": 66.72,
   "text": "Want more places that break the map?"
  },
  {
   "start": 67.18,
   "end": 67.94,
   "text": "Follow stack tags."
  }
 ]
}